div.div:
1. Graph the interfaces as 'embedding sequences' (variables applied to some base like the definition network/vector of the interface concept).
The reason you graph it this way is to identify useful relevant cross-interface structures, like 'structures with similar variation across interfaces' or 'structures with useful variation (like opposing variation) for some intent (like completing a structure)' or 'patterns across interfaces'.

3. Each of these interface structures has a related 'network of graphs' which can make it trivial to identify useful structures like 'functions that can be added to create a higher value for this variable'. Graph these variable interactions and compare them for the set (abstract patterns and independence patterns) so that useful interactions for each problem-solving intent (like 'completing a structure') are identified.
What this step involves is 'matching "queries of these networks of graphs associated with each interface structure" with "queries of a network of problem-solving intents" or "queries of a network of solution metrics" (this can be an additional step).
